&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;&lt;&#x2F;pre&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;trading-places&quot;&gt;Trading Places&lt;&#x2F;h2&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;My friends Hannah and Steven from college are starting up a new fintech
company. They sent me the link to their trading platform so I can take a look
(in demo mode). It’s supposedly quite secure, using the latest in
cryptographic standards.&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Why don’t you take &lt;a href=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;host5.metaproblems.com:7606&#x2F;&quot;&gt;a look&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;?&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The site provides &lt;code&gt;guest&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;:&lt;code&gt;guest&lt;&#x2F;code&gt; credentials to authenticate, after which it
kindly informs users that:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Guest preview mode enabled - &lt;code&gt;admin&lt;&#x2F;code&gt; login required to make trades.&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once authenticated, we’re provided a JWT. However, the actual process that sets
said JWT is a little odd:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
