&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;&lt;&#x2F;pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;…and importing that as “raw data” into Audacity, mostly with defaults but
some tweaks after some trial and error:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Encoding: Signed 32-bit PCM&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Byte order: No endianess&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;…yields and voice &lt;em&gt;speaking far too quickly&lt;&#x2F;em&gt; and saying something along the
lines of:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;“em-ee-tee-ey-see-tee-eff-curly-bracket-four-underscore-ell-one-ton-tee-ell…”&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Playing around with playback speeds and enjoying the goofy baritone, I &lt;em&gt;think&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;
it’s spelling (although there’s some educated guessing as “one tonne tee”
doesn’t quite make sense):&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;pre data-lang=&quot;txt&quot; class=&quot;language-txt z-code&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-txt&quot; data-lang=&quot;txt&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;z-text z-plain&quot;&gt;MetaCTF{4_l1ttl3_b1rd_t0ld_m3}
&lt;&#x2F;span&gt;&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;&lt;&#x2F;pre&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;pikalang&quot;&gt;Pikalang&lt;&#x2F;h2&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I just heard about this cool new esoteric programming language called
&lt;a href=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;esolangs.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Pikalang&quot;&gt;Pikalang&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;!&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;It has no silly strcpy()’s or heaps, so it must be *super effective* against
hackers.&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Download my interpreter
&lt;a href=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;metaproblems.com&#x2F;975e1fca9a16fafeee7ba12927da5b29&#x2F;pikalang.zip&quot;&gt;here&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;!&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;If you’d like to try running some Pikalang code, do so here:
&lt;code&gt;nc kubenode.mctf.io 30013&lt;&#x2F;code&gt;&lt;&#x2F;em&gt;&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;blockquote&gt;
